 the role of a good death in a good life. He stresses the universality of death, its importance as life's final rite of passage, and its ability to liberate us from pain, slavery, or political oppression. Featuring beautifully rendered new translations, How to Die also includes an enlightening introduction, notes, the original Latin texts, and an epilogue presenting Tacitus's description of Seneca's grim suicide.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Jan 2023) 0aConduct of lifevEarly works to 1800. 0aDeathvEarly works to 1800. 0aEthicsvEarly works to 1800. 7aPHILOSOPHY / History & Surveys / Ancient & Classical.2bisacsh  a30s BC.  aAdiaphora.  aAdolescence.  aAeneid.  aAll Fools.  aAll things.  aAnnals (Tacitus).  aAssassination.  aAsthma.  aAstyages.  aAufidius Bassus.  aAutocracy.  aBattle of Carrhae.  aBoredom.  aBreakup.  aBurial.  aCacus.  aCambyses II.  aCarriage.  aCato the Younger.  aCertainty.  aChief Adviser.  aCruelty.  aDe Providentia.  aDecimus (praenomen).  aDecimus Junius Brutus (consul 77 BC).  aDiscourses of Epictetus.  aDisfigurement.  aDisgust.  aEloquence.  aEpicureanism.  aEpistle.  aEquanimity.  aEunuch.  aFirst Order (Star Wars).  aFoe (novel).  aForced suicide.  aGreatness.  aHallucinogen.  aHarpagus.  aHuman body.  aIn Death.  aMarcia (gens).  aMarcia (mistress of Commodus).  aMarcia (wife of Cato the Younger).  aMarcus Aemilius Lepidus (triumvir).  aMarcus Licinius Crassus.  aMarcus Porcius Cato (son of Cato the Younger).  aMark Antony.  aMeal.  aMonth.  aMurder.  aOrcus.  aPalinurus.  aPhalaris.  aPhilosopher.  aPhilosophy.  aPhlegm.  aPity.  aPolitician.  aPompeia Paulina.  aPompey.  aPrincipate.  aProse.  aPsilocybin.  aPsychedelic experience.  aQuantity.  aReincarna